B.QT=new A.t("A child with short stature, webbed neck, and coarctation of the aorta most likely has which condition?",B.Je,2,"Turner syndrome (45,X) presents with short stature, webbed neck, shield chest, coarctation of the aorta, primary amenorrhea, and mostly normal IQ.")
B.Kf=s(["1-5%","10-30%","50-70%","80-90%"],t.s)
B.P1=new A.t("What percentage of children with Down syndrome have atlantoaxial instability?",B.Kf,1,"Atlantoaxial instability is present in 10-30% of individuals with Down syndrome. Flexion/extension cervical spine radiographs are recommended before participation in Special Olympics.")
B.Gy=s(["Maternal allele","Paternal allele","Both alleles equally","X-linked allele"],t.s)
B.QQ=new A.t("Prader-Willi syndrome results from loss of function of genes on which parental allele at chromosome 15q11-q13?",B.Gy,1,"Prader-Willi syndrome results from loss of paternally expressed genes at 15q11-q13, while loss of maternally expressed genes at the same locus causes Angelman syndrome. This is the paradigmatic example of genomic imprinting.")
B.GH=s(["Karyotype","Chromosomal microarray","DNA methylation analysis","Whole exome sequencing"],t.s)
B.QO=new A.t("What is the gold standard diagnostic test for Prader-Willi syndrome?",B.GH,2,"DNA methylation analysis is the gold standard for Prader-Willi syndrome because it detects more than 99% of cases regardless of the underlying mechanism (deletion, uniparental disomy, or imprinting defect).")
B.GW=s(["Angelman syndrome","Prader-Willi syndrome","Down syndrome","Rett syndrome"],t.s)
B.O2=new A.t("A neonate presents with severe hypotonia, poor feeding requiring gavage, and cryptorchidism. By age 4, he develops insatiable appetite and progressive obesity. Which condition best fits this two-phase pattern?",B.GW,1,"The two-phase pattern of neonatal hypotonia with poor feeding followed by childhood hyperphagia and obesity is the hallmark of Prader-Willi syndrome. The hypothalamic dysfunction drives the insatiable appetite in the second phase.")
B.Ia=s(["Infantile spasms with hypsarrhythmia","Seizures with high-amplitude 2-3 Hz delta activity","Absence seizures with 3 Hz spike-and-wave","Generalized tonic-clonic with normal EEG"],t.s)
B.On=new A.t("Which seizure pattern and EEG finding is characteristic of Angelman syndrome?",B.Ia,1,"Angelman syndrome is characterized by seizures in 80-90% of patients with onset at 1-3 years and a characteristic EEG pattern of high-amplitude 2-3 Hz delta activity. This EEG finding can suggest the diagnosis before genetic confirmation.")
B.Gk=s(["CAG","CTG","CGG","GAA"],t.s)
B.Pc=new A.t("Fragile X syndrome is caused by expansion of which trinucleotide repeat in the FMR1 gene?",B.Gk,2,"Fragile X is caused by CGG trinucleotide repeat expansion in the FMR1 gene at Xq27.3. A full mutation (>200 repeats) silences FMR1 through methylation. It is the most common inherited cause of intellectual disability.")
B.HS=s(["Klinefelter syndrome","Fragile X syndrome","Williams syndrome","Prader-Willi syndrome"],t.s)
B.Oj=new A.t("A post-pubertal male with intellectual disability, long face, prominent jaw, large ears, and large testes is most likely to have which condition?",B.HS,1,"Macro-orchidism (large testes) in a post-pubertal male with intellectual disability, long face, prominent jaw, and large ears is the classic presentation of Fragile X syndrome. Macro-orchidism is present in approximately 80% of affected males.")
B.Hn=s(["Father only","Mother only","Either parent equally","Neither \u2014 expansions occur de novo"],t.s)
B.Od=new A.t("In Fragile X syndrome, premutation alleles expand to full mutations during transmission from which parent?",B.Hn,1,"Premutation alleles (55-200 CGG repeats) are unstable during maternal transmission and may expand to full mutations. Paternal premutation alleles are generally stable. This maternal transmission pattern explains the phenomenon of genetic anticipation in Fragile X.")
B.Gz=s(["FMR1","UBE3A","MECP2","ELN"],t.s)
B.P_=new A.t("A 3-year-old girl who had normal development until 18 months now demonstrates loss of purposeful hand use, repetitive hand-wringing movements, and acquired microcephaly. Which gene is responsible?",B.Gz,2,"Rett syndrome is caused by mutations in MECP2 at Xq28. The triad of regression after normal early development, loss of purposeful hand use replaced by stereotypic hand-wringing, and acquired microcephaly is the hallmark. It occurs almost exclusively in females.")
B.Hk=s(["Endocardial cushion defect","Coarctation of the aorta","Supravalvular aortic stenosis","Patent ductus arteriosus"],t.s)
B.Pk=new A.t("Which cardiac defect is the classic board association with Williams syndrome?",B.Hk,2,"Supravalvular aortic stenosis (SVAS) occurs in 75% of Williams syndrome patients and results from haploinsufficiency of the elastin gene within the 7q11.23 microdeletion. Peripheral pulmonary stenosis is also common in infancy.")
B.K9=s(["Fragile X syndrome","Williams syndrome","Angelman syndrome","Prader-Willi syndrome"],t.s)
B.Ow=new A.t('A child is described as overly friendly with a "cocktail party personality," strong verbal skills, but severe visuospatial deficits and elfin facies. Which syndrome is most likely?',B.K9,1,'Williams syndrome (7q11.23 deletion) has one of the most distinctive cognitive profiles: remarkably strong verbal and social skills with severe visuospatial deficits. The overly friendly, gregarious personality with lack of stranger anxiety is termed the "cocktail party personality."')
B.EX=s(["Trisomy 21","Trisomy 18","Trisomy 13","Trisomy 16"],t.s)
B.PY=new A.t("A growth-restricted neonate has clenched fists with the index finger overlapping the third finger and the fifth finger overlapping the fourth, along with rocker-bottom feet and a prominent occiput. Which trisomy is most likely?",B.EX,1,"The combination of overlapping fingers (index over third, fifth over fourth) with clenched fists, rocker-bottom feet, and prominent occiput is considered pathognomonic for trisomy 18 (Edwards syndrome). Approximately 90% die by age 1 year.")
B.Hq=s(["Trisomy 21","Trisomy 18","Trisomy 13","Turner syndrome"],t.s)
B.Rd=new A.t("A neonate presents with midline cleft lip, holoprosencephaly, and postaxial polydactyly. Which trisomy is most likely?",B.Hq,2,"Trisomy 13 (Patau syndrome) is distinguished by midline defects \u2014 holoprosencephaly, midline cleft lip, and cutis aplasia \u2014 combined with postaxial polydactyly. Unlike trisomy 18 which features hand/foot deformities, trisomy 13 features midline brain defects.")
B.F_=s(["Toxoplasmosis","Rubella","Cytomegalovirus (CMV)","Herpes simplex"],t.s)
B.Pf=new A.t("A newborn with congenital hearing loss has periventricular intracranial calcifications on head CT. Which congenital infection is the most likely cause?",B.F_,2,"CMV is the most common congenital infection and produces periventricular calcifications. Toxoplasmosis produces scattered/diffuse intracranial calcifications. CMV is also the leading non-genetic cause of sensorineural hearing loss in children.")
B.Hx=s(["1 or more","2 or more","3 or more","5 or more"],t.s)
B.Qp=new A.t("How many component features are required for the diagnosis of VACTERL association?",B.Hx,2,"VACTERL diagnosis requires 3 or more features (Vertebral, Anal atresia, Cardiac, Tracheoesophageal fistula, Esophageal atresia, Renal anomalies, Limb defects). It is an association, not a syndrome, because no single unifying genetic cause has been identified.")
B.H9=s(["Karyotype","Chromosomal microarray (CMA)","Whole exome sequencing (WES)","FISH analysis"],t.s)
B.NX=new A.t("What is the recommended first-tier genetic test for a child with unexplained developmental delay or intellectual disability?",B.H9,1,"Per ACMG consensus, chromosomal microarray (CMA) has replaced karyotype as the first-tier test for unexplained DD/ID, with a diagnostic yield of 15-20% compared to only 3% for karyotype. However, karyotype is still needed when a balanced translocation is suspected since CMA cannot detect balanced rearrangements.")
B.K8=s(["4 months","6-8 months","10-14 months","18-24 months"],t.s)
B.OO=new A.t("At what age does the anterior fontanelle typically close?",B.K8,2,"The anterior fontanelle normally closes between 10 and 14 months of age but may remain open until 18 months. The posterior fontanelle closes by 4 months.")
B.Iq=s(["Moro reflex","Palmar grasp","Plantar grasp","Rooting reflex"],t.s)
B.Rj=new A.t("Which primitive reflex persists the longest before integration?",B.Iq,2,"The plantar grasp reflex integrates at 9-12 months, which is later than the Moro (4-6 months), palmar grasp (4-6 months), and rooting reflex (3-4 months).")
B.HY=s(["6 months","9 months","12 months","15 months"],t.s)
B.NU=new A.t("A child who cannot sit independently by what age should raise a developmental red flag?",B.HY,1,"Key developmental red flags include: no social smile by 3 months, not sitting by 9 months, not walking by 18 months, no words by 18 months, no 2-word phrases by 24 months.")
