B.PU=new A.t("Untreated Kawasaki disease results in coronary artery aneurysms in approximately 25% of cases. Timely IVIG administration within how many days of fever onset reduces this risk to less than 5%?",B.J7,3,"IVIG (2 g/kg as a single infusion) given within 10 days of fever onset reduces the rate of coronary artery aneurysms from approximately 25% to less than 5%. Infants under 6 months are at highest risk and more likely to have an incomplete presentation.")
B.IS=s(["Bilateral non-exudative conjunctival injection","Strawberry tongue and cracked lips","Vesicular rash","Cervical lymphadenopathy \u22651.5 cm"],t.s)
B.NW=new A.t("Classic Kawasaki disease requires fever for 5 or more days plus at least 4 of 5 clinical features. Which of the following is NOT one of the 5 features?",B.IS,2,"The 5 features of Kawasaki disease are: bilateral non-exudative conjunctival injection, oral mucous membrane changes (strawberry tongue, cracked lips), polymorphous exanthem (which is NOT vesicular), extremity changes (edema/erythema acutely, periungual desquamation in convalescence), and cervical lymphadenopathy \u22651.5 cm.")
B.Gv=s(["Prolonged PR interval","Fever \u226538.5\xb0C","Polyarthralgia","Sydenham chorea"],t.s)
B.Ru=new A.t("Which of the following is a MAJOR criterion in the revised Jones Criteria (2015) for acute rheumatic fever in low-risk populations?",B.Gv,3,"The 5 major Jones criteria in low-risk populations are: carditis (clinical or subclinical), polyarthritis, Sydenham chorea, erythema marginatum, and subcutaneous nodules. Fever, polyarthralgia, elevated ESR/CRP, and prolonged PR interval are minor criteria.")
B.JD=s(["40%","75%","93.1%","99.6%"],t.s)
B.OY=new A.t("A child with hip pain has all 4 Kocher criteria positive (non-weight-bearing, ESR >40, fever >38.5\xb0C, WBC >12,000). What is the predicted probability of septic arthritis?",B.JD,3,"Kocher criteria predicted probabilities: 0 criteria = <0.2%, 1 = 3%, 2 = 40%, 3 = 93.1%, 4 = 99.6%. Caird et al. later added CRP >2.0 mg/dL as a 5th criterion with the strongest independent predictive value.")
B.K6=s(["Western blot first, then ELISA if positive","ELISA first, then Western blot if positive or equivocal","PCR first, then ELISA if negative","Blood culture first, then ELISA if negative"],t.s)
B.Qo=new A.t("The two-tier serologic testing protocol for Lyme disease consists of which sequence?",B.K6,1,"Two-tier Lyme testing: Step 1 is ELISA (screening). If positive or equivocal, step 2 is Western blot (confirmatory). IgM Western blot requires 2 of 3 bands (valid only within first 30 days); IgG requires 5 of 10 bands. A modified two-tier approach using two sequential EIAs was FDA-approved in 2019.")
B.GE=s(["JIA is defined by arthritis persisting for \u226512 weeks; adult RA requires \u22656 weeks","RF-positive disease is the most common JIA subtype","Uveitis in JIA is typically chronic and asymptomatic, whereas adult RA-associated eye disease is rare","JIA does not produce pannus formation or joint erosions"],t.s)
B.R4=new A.t("Which of the following is a key difference between JIA and adult rheumatoid arthritis?",B.GE,2,"A major difference is that chronic anterior uveitis is common in JIA (especially ANA-positive oligoarticular) and is characteristically asymptomatic, requiring slit-lamp screening. RF-positive polyarticular JIA (which mimics adult RA) accounts for only 2\u20137% of JIA cases. JIA does produce pannus formation and can cause erosions.")
B.Jm=s(["CD20 inhibitors (rituximab)","T-cell co-stimulation blockers (abatacept)","IL-1 or IL-6 inhibitors (anakinra, canakinumab, tocilizumab)","JAK inhibitors (tofacitinib)"],t.s)
B.ON=new A.t("For systemic JIA, the 2019 ACR guidelines recommend which class of biologic agents as first-line therapy over TNF inhibitors?",B.Jm,2,"Systemic JIA is an autoinflammatory disease driven by the IL-1/IL-6 axis rather than TNF pathways. The 2019 ACR guidelines strongly recommend IL-1 inhibitors (anakinra, canakinumab) or IL-6 inhibitors (tocilizumab) as first-line biologic therapy for sJIA.")
B.GJ=s(["Baricitinib","Tofacitinib","Upadacitinib","Ruxolitinib"],t.s)
B.PJ=new A.t("Which of the following is the first JAK inhibitor FDA-approved for polyarticular JIA?",B.GJ,1,"Tofacitinib (Xeljanz) is the first JAK inhibitor (JAK1/3, oral small molecule) approved for polyarticular JIA in children age 2 years and older. Other FDA-approved JIA biologics include etanercept, adalimumab, golimumab, abatacept, tocilizumab, and canakinumab.")
B.JY=s(["Malar rash and discoid lesions","Heliotrope rash and Gottron papules","V-sign and shawl sign","Nail fold capillary changes and calcinosis"],t.s)
B.Rf=new A.t("Which two skin findings are considered PATHOGNOMONIC for juvenile dermatomyositis?",B.JY,1,"The heliotrope rash (violaceous discoloration of the upper eyelids with periorbital edema) and Gottron papules (erythematous papules over the MCP, PIP, and DIP joints) are pathognomonic for dermatomyositis. Unlike adult DM, JDM does not carry an increased risk of underlying malignancy.")
B.JE=s(["Order ELISA and Western blot before treating","Start empiric doxycycline without serologic testing","Obtain a skin biopsy of the lesion","Observe and recheck in 2 weeks"],t.s)
B.OT=new A.t("A 10-year-old from Connecticut presents with a single expanding annular rash measuring 8 cm on his thigh after a recent camping trip. The most appropriate next step is:",B.JE,1,"Erythema migrans (expanding annular rash \u22655 cm) is diagnostic of early localized Lyme disease without the need for serology. Treatment should be started empirically. Serologic testing is NOT indicated for EM because it may be negative early in the disease.")
B.FX=s(["ERA uveitis is chronic, asymptomatic, and anterior; oligoarticular is posterior","ERA uveitis is acute, symptomatic (red painful eye); oligoarticular is chronic and asymptomatic","Both types are chronic and asymptomatic","ERA does not cause uveitis"],t.s)
B.OP=new A.t("How does the uveitis associated with enthesitis-related arthritis (ERA) differ from the uveitis of oligoarticular JIA?",B.FX,1,"ERA-associated uveitis is acute anterior uveitis that is SYMPTOMATIC (red, painful eye), similar to adult ankylosing spondylitis. Oligoarticular JIA uveitis is chronic anterior uveitis that is characteristically ASYMPTOMATIC, requiring routine slit-lamp screening.")
B.FD=s(["Flame burns","Electrical burns","Scald burns","Chemical burns"],t.s)
B.Pg=new A.t("What is the most common type of burn injury in the pediatric population?",B.FD,2,"Scald burns are the single most common cause of pediatric burn injury, with the highest incidence occurring in toddlers. This differs from adults where flame burns predominate.")
B.F4=s(["9%","14%","18%","22%"],t.s)
B.QJ=new A.t("Using the modified Rule of 9s for a 2-year-old child, what percentage of total body surface area does the head represent?",B.F4,2,"In the pediatric modified Rule of 9s, the head = 18% (vs 9% in adults) and each leg = 14% (vs 18% in adults). The Lund and Browder chart is the most accurate method.")
B.I7=s(["The need for pain management during therapy","Anti-deformity positioning is the opposite of comfortable positions","Comfort measures should be prioritized over range of motion","Contractures are inevitable regardless of positioning"],t.s)
B.QB=new A.t('In pediatric burn rehabilitation, the phrase "COMFORT = CONTRACTURE" refers to:',B.I7,1,"In burn rehabilitation, the position of comfort promotes contracture formation. Anti-deformity positioning (which opposes the comfortable position) is essential to prevent contractures.")
B.FJ=s(["Rule of Nines","Palmar method","Lund-Browder chart","Berkow formula"],t.s)
B.Qn=new A.t("What is the gold standard method for estimating total body surface area (TBSA) of burns in children?",B.FJ,2,"The Lund-Browder chart is the gold standard for pediatric TBSA estimation because it provides age-specific percentages that account for the changing body proportions as children grow (e.g., head decreases from 19% in infants to 7% in adults).")
B.IN=s(["Superficial (first degree)","Superficial partial-thickness (superficial second degree)","Full-thickness (third degree)","Fourth degree (subdermal)"],t.s)
B.Qs=new A.t("Which burn depth is the MOST painful?",B.IN,1,"Superficial partial-thickness burns are the most painful because intact nerve endings in the papillary dermis are exposed and stimulated. Pain inversely correlates with burn depth: full-thickness and fourth-degree burns are insensate because nerve endings have been destroyed.")
B.Jn=s(["Wrist flexion, MCPs extended, IPs flexed",'MCPs flexed 70\u201390 degrees, IPs extended, thumb abducted ("intrinsic plus")',"Full fist position with thumb tucked","Wrist neutral, all fingers fully extended"],t.s)
B.OC=new A.t("A child sustains a dorsal hand burn. Without proper positioning, the expected contracture deformity is MCP hyperextension, IP flexion, and thumb adduction. The correct anti-deformity position is:",B.Jn,1,'The dorsal hand burn leads to "claw hand" deformity. The anti-deformity "safe position" or "intrinsic plus" position maintains MCPs in 70\u201390 degrees of flexion (keeping collateral ligaments at maximum length), IPs in extension, and the thumb in abduction and opposition.')
B.HH=s(["Neck flexion with a pillow","Neck extension with no pillow and a towel roll under the shoulders","Neck lateral flexion toward the burn","Neck neutral with a cervical collar"],t.s)
B.Oe=new A.t("For an anterior neck burn, the anti-deformity position is:",B.HH,1,"Anterior neck burns lead to flexion contracture. The anti-deformity position is neck extension, achieved by removing the pillow and placing a towel roll under the shoulders. The principle of COMFORT = CONTRACTURE means the comfortable flexed position promotes contracture.")
B.Ki=s(["Accidental scald from a pulled pot","Contact burn from a heating pad","Forced immersion burn (non-accidental trauma)","Chemical burn from a household cleaner"],t.s)
B.R0=new A.t("A 2-year-old presents with deep burns of the buttocks and posterior thighs with central sparing of the buttock skin. This pattern is most consistent with:",B.Ki,2,'The "doughnut sign" \u2014 central sparing of the buttocks surrounded by deep burns \u2014 is pathognomonic for forced immersion. The buttocks press against the cooler bottom of the tub, creating a central spared zone. This pattern cannot be explained by accidental immersion.')
B.H7=s(["Irregular, asymmetric splash pattern with variable depth","Symmetric stocking/glove distribution with uniform depth and clear demarcation lines","Partial-thickness burn on the hand with blistering","Superficial sunburn on the shoulders"],t.s)
B.Rm=new A.t("Which of the following burn presentations is MOST suspicious for non-accidental trauma?",B.H7,1,"NAT burn indicators include: symmetric stocking/glove distribution with clear demarcation (forced immersion), uniform burn depth (prolonged forced contact), sparing of flexion creases, delay in seeking care >2 hours, and history inconsistent with the burn pattern.")
B.Kj=s(["10\u201315 mmHg for 6 months","23\u201325 mmHg for 12\u201318 months (23 hours/day)","30\u201340 mmHg for 6 months","15\u201320 mmHg for 24 months (12 hours/day)"],t.s)
B.P8=new A.t("Custom pressure garments for burn scar management should deliver how much pressure and be worn for what duration?",B.Kj,1,"Custom pressure garments delivering 23\u201325 mmHg are worn 23 hours per day for 12\u201318 months or until scar maturation (scar becomes flat, soft, and pale). They reduce scar thickness and are a standard component of comprehensive burn rehabilitation.")
B.F1=s(["20\u201330%","40\u201350%","60\u201380%","90\u201395%"],t.s)
B.R9=new A.t("In children under 5 years of age, what percentage of pediatric burns are scald burns?",B.F1,2,"Scald burns account for 60\u201380% of pediatric burns in children under 5 years due to their exploratory behavior, short stature, and limited ability to escape a heat source. In older children and adolescents, flame burns become the leading mechanism.")
B.I5=s(["3\u20135 days","7\u201310 days","14\u201321 days","30\u201345 days"],t.s)
B.Rc=new A.t("Burns that take longer than what duration to heal have a significantly higher risk of hypertrophic scarring?",B.I5,2,"Burns that take longer than 14\u201321 days to heal have significantly higher risk of hypertrophic scarring. Deep partial-thickness and full-thickness burns therefore carry the greatest scarring risk. Hypertrophic scars remain within wound boundaries and tend to regress, unlike keloids.")
B.Go=s(["Shoulder adduction and internal rotation","Shoulder abduction to 90 degrees with an airplane splint","Shoulder flexion to 180 degrees","Shoulder extension and adduction"],t.s)
B.R6=new A.t("For a burn involving the axilla and shoulder, the expected contracture position is adduction. The correct anti-deformity position is:",B.Go,1,"Axillary/shoulder burns lead to adduction contracture. The anti-deformity position is shoulder abduction to 90 degrees, maintained with an airplane splint. This opposes the natural tendency to adduct, which the COMFORT = CONTRACTURE principle warns against.")
B.FH=s(["Brain tumors","Neuroblastoma","Acute lymphoblastic leukemia (ALL)","Osteosarcoma"],t.s)
B.Qz=new A.t("What is the most common childhood malignancy?",B.FH,2,"ALL accounts for approximately 80% of childhood leukemias and 30% of all pediatric cancers. Peak incidence occurs between ages 2-5 years.")
B.FE=s(["Diaphysis","Metaphysis","Epiphysis","Periosteum"],t.s)
B.Ph=new A.t("Osteosarcoma most commonly arises in which anatomic location of the bone?",B.FE,1,"Osteosarcoma typically arises in the metaphysis of long bones, most commonly around the knee (distal femur, proximal tibia). Ewing sarcoma occurs in the diaphysis.")
B.G0=s(["Acute lymphoblastic leukemia (ALL)","Acute myeloid leukemia (AML)","Chronic myeloid leukemia (CML)","Non-Hodgkin lymphoma"],t.s)
B.O1=new A.t("A 7-year-old presents with fatigue, bruising, and a WBC of 60,000. Peripheral smear shows blast cells with needle-shaped crystalline inclusions in the cytoplasm. These findings are pathognomonic for:",B.G0,1,"Auer rods \u2014 needle-shaped crystalline inclusions visible in blast cell cytoplasm \u2014 are pathognomonic for AML. They are especially prominent in acute promyelocytic leukemia (APL/M3), which is treated with ATRA plus arsenic trioxide and carries a unique risk of DIC.")
B.Jx=s(["Osteosarcoma","Ewing sarcoma","Osteochondroma","Aneurysmal bone cyst"],t.s)
B.OZ=new A.t('A 12-year-old presents with leg pain and fever. Radiographs show a permeative lesion in the femoral diaphysis with "onion skin" periosteal reaction. The most likely diagnosis is:',B.Jx,1,'Ewing sarcoma arises in the diaphysis and shows an "onion skin" periosteal reaction with a permeative/moth-eaten pattern. It is a small round blue cell tumor with the t(11;22) EWSR1-FLI1 fusion in ~85% of cases. It is notably rare in African Americans.')
B.Jp=s(["Quadriceps femoris","Hamstrings","Ankle plantarflexors (gastrocnemius-soleus)","Hip adductors"],t.s)
B.QD=new A.t('After a Van Ness rotationplasty for a distal femur osteosarcoma, which muscle group functions as the "knee extensors"?',B.Jp,2,'In Van Ness rotationplasty, the distal limb is rotated 180 degrees so the ankle joint functions as a biological knee joint. Because of this rotation, the ankle plantarflexors (gastrocnemius-soleus) now function as "knee extensors." The procedure converts an above-knee amputation into a functional below-knee amputation.')
B.Gu=s(["Neuroblastoma","Wilms tumor","CNS tumors","Osteosarcoma"],t.s)
B.Qb=new A.t("The most common solid tumor in children is:",B.Gu,2,"CNS tumors are the most common solid tumors in children, accounting for approximately 25% of pediatric cancers. Neuroblastoma is the most common extracranial solid tumor. Leukemia (ALL) is the most common pediatric malignancy overall (~30%).")
B.Il=s(['"Onion skin" periosteal reaction','"Sunburst" pattern and Codman triangle','"Soap bubble" appearance','"Punched out" lytic lesion'],t.s)
B.Qy=new A.t("Which radiographic finding is characteristic of osteosarcoma?",B.Il,1,'Osteosarcoma shows a "sunburst" pattern of radiating periosteal new bone and Codman triangle (periosteal elevation). It arises in the metaphysis of long bones, most commonly around the knee. Ewing sarcoma shows "onion skin" periosteal reaction in the diaphysis.')
B.HL=s(["Osteosarcoma","Ewing sarcoma","Giant cell tumor","Unicameral bone cyst"],t.s)
B.O7=new A.t('On a board examination, a question asks: "Which bone tumor characteristically arises in the epiphysis?" The correct answer is:',B.HL,2,"Giant cell tumor and chondroblastoma are the epiphyseal bone tumors. Giant cell tumor extends to the subchondral bone, most commonly in the distal femur, proximal tibia, and distal radius. Osteosarcoma and osteochondroma arise in the metaphysis; Ewing sarcoma in the diaphysis.")
B.IR=s(["Methotrexate","Doxorubicin","Vincristine","Cyclophosphamide"],t.s)
B.R8=new A.t("A child receiving chemotherapy for ALL develops bilateral foot drop and distal numbness. The most likely causative agent is:",B.IR,2,"Vincristine-induced peripheral neuropathy is the most important rehabilitation-relevant side effect during ALL treatment. It presents as distal sensorimotor neuropathy with foot drop, numbness, and pain. It is a dose-limiting toxicity.")
B.Ha=s(["10,000/uL","50,000/uL","100,000/uL","150,000/uL"],t.s)
B.OE=new A.t("During active cancer treatment, high-intensity exercise should be avoided when the platelet count falls below:",B.Ha,1,"Exercise precautions during cancer treatment: avoid high-intensity exercise if platelets <50,000/uL (bleeding risk) or ANC <500/uL (infection risk). Supervised aerobic and resistance training are safe during treatment and reduce cancer-related fatigue.")
B.I_=s(["Osteosarcoma is radiosensitive; Ewing sarcoma is not","Ewing sarcoma is radiosensitive; osteosarcoma is not","Both tumors are equally radiosensitive","Neither tumor responds to radiation"],t.s)
B.OF=new A.t("A key difference between osteosarcoma and Ewing sarcoma that affects local control strategy is:",B.I_,1,"Ewing sarcoma is radiosensitive, so radiation can be used for local control when surgical resection is not feasible (e.g., sacral or pelvic locations). Osteosarcoma is NOT radiosensitive and requires wide surgical resection for local control.")
B.F2=s(["Prolonged bed rest","Supervised aerobic and resistance exercise","Psychostimulant medications","Unlimited sedentary activity"],t.s)
B.Rb=new A.t("What is the most effective intervention for cancer-related fatigue in pediatric cancer patients?",B.F2,1,"Exercise is the most effective intervention for cancer-related fatigue in both adults and children. Supervised aerobic and resistance training programs are safe during active cancer treatment and improve fitness, reduce fatigue, and enhance quality of life.")
B.Jo=s(["Cancer","Congenital anomalies","Traumatic brain injury","Infectious disease"],t.s)
B.Q4=new A.t("What is the leading cause of death in children over 1 year of age?",B.Jo,2,"TBI is the #1 cause of death and disability in children over 1 year of age. Annually, 185 children per 100,000 experience TBI.")
B.GI=s(["Higher bone mineral density","Ligamentous laxity and proportionally larger head","Increased spinal cord blood flow","More developed vertebral bodies"],t.s)
B.Rg=new A.t("SCIWORA (Spinal Cord Injury Without Radiographic Abnormality) is more common in children due to:",B.GI,1,"SCIWORA is more common in children because of ligamentous laxity, proportionally larger head size, and immature vertebral bodies that allow greater spinal column stretch without bony fracture.")
B.HQ=s(["Return to play","Return to learn","Full contact practice","Competitive sports participation"],t.s)
B.Or=new A.t("In pediatric concussion management, which should occur FIRST?",B.HQ,1,"Current guidelines (2023 Berlin consensus) recommend return-to-LEARN before return-to-PLAY. Brief relative rest (24-48 hours) followed by sub-symptom threshold activity is recommended.")
B.Jv=s(["Oriented speech","Coos and babbles with age-appropriate vocalizations","Irritable crying but consolable","Cries only to pain"],t.s)
B.QM=new A.t("On the modified pediatric GCS for children younger than 2 years, a verbal score of 5 corresponds to which response?",B.Jv,1,'In the pediatric GCS for preverbal children (<2 years), the verbal scale is modified: 5 = coos/babbles (age-appropriate), 4 = irritable/consolable crying, 3 = cries to pain, 2 = inconsolable/agitated, 1 = none. This replaces the standard "oriented" verbal response used for older children.')
B.I2=s(["GCS of 14 or below","Altered mental status","Signs of basilar skull fracture","Palpable skull fracture"],t.s)
B.PO=new A.t("In the PECARN decision rules, which finding is a high-risk criterion for children aged 2 years and OLDER but NOT for children younger than 2 years?",B.I2,2,"Signs of basilar skull fracture (hemotympanum, raccoon eyes, Battle sign, CSF otorrhea/rhinorrhea) are high-risk criteria in the PECARN algorithm for children >= 2 years. For children < 2 years, palpable skull fracture is used instead. GCS 14 or below and altered mental status are high-risk in both age groups.")
B.Ke=s(["Greater than 2 feet","Greater than 3 feet","Greater than 5 feet","Greater than 10 feet"],t.s)
B.R2=new A.t("According to PECARN, what is the severe mechanism fall-height threshold for a child younger than 2 years?",B.Ke,1,"The PECARN fall-height thresholds differ by age: > 3 feet for children < 2 years and > 5 feet for children >= 2 years. Falls exceeding these thresholds are considered a severe mechanism and place the child in the intermediate-risk category.")
B.Gc=s(["Epidural hematoma","Retinal hemorrhages","Periorbital ecchymoses","Depressed skull fracture"],t.s)
B.Om=new A.t("The classic triad of findings in abusive head trauma consists of subdural hemorrhage, encephalopathy, and which additional finding?",B.Gc,1,"The classic abusive head trauma triad is: (1) subdural hemorrhage (often bilateral or interhemispheric), (2) retinal hemorrhages (characteristically multilayered, bilateral, extending to the periphery), and (3) encephalopathy/cerebral edema. Peak age is 2-4 months. All three elements need not be present for diagnosis.")
B.H3=s(["Toddlers; repeated falls from standing height","Adolescent male athletes; a second concussion before full recovery from the first","Elderly patients; subdural hematoma recurrence","Infants; abusive head trauma with repeat shaking"],t.s)
B.Q6=new A.t("Second impact syndrome occurs almost exclusively in which demographic group and results from which mechanism?",B.H3,1,"Second impact syndrome describes rapid, catastrophic cerebral edema when a second concussion is sustained before recovery from a prior concussion. It occurs almost exclusively in adolescent male athletes. Loss of cerebrovascular autoregulation leads to massive brain swelling with mortality approaching 50%.")
B.GP=s(["Strict cognitive and physical rest for 2 weeks is mandatory","Symptom-limited activity within 24-48 hours replaces prolonged strict rest","CT imaging is required for all concussions","Return to play may occur same day if symptoms resolve within 15 minutes"],t.s)
B.Ri=new A.t("Which key change was introduced by the Amsterdam 2022 (6th International) concussion consensus?",B.GP,1,'The Amsterdam 2022 consensus shifted away from the previously advocated "cocoon" approach. Prolonged physical and cognitive rest beyond 24-48 hours is not beneficial and may be harmful. Early return to light, symptom-limited physical activity within the first 2 days is now encouraged.')
B.JC=s(["Post-traumatic epilepsy","Growing into deficits","Second impact syndrome","Chronic traumatic encephalopathy"],t.s)
B.PW=new A.t("A child who sustained a severe TBI at age 3 performs adequately in early elementary school but begins failing in middle school. This phenomenon is best described as:",B.JC,1,'"Growing into deficits" describes the phenomenon unique to pediatric TBI where children appear to recover well initially but manifest increasingly apparent cognitive and behavioral deficits as developmental demands escalate. Frontal lobe functions (executive function, planning, abstract reasoning) mature during late childhood and adolescence, and early injuries disrupt the foundation for this development.')
B.Ii=s(["Type I: Major intramedullary hemorrhage","Type II: Minor focal hemorrhage","Type III: Cord edema only","Type IV: Normal MRI"],t.s)
B.Q2=new A.t("In the Pang classification of SCIWORA, which MRI finding carries the BEST prognosis?",B.Ii,3,"Pang Type IV SCIWORA has a completely normal MRI and carries the best prognosis, likely representing transient cord concussion or neuropraxia. Type III (edema only) has a good prognosis. Type I (major hemorrhage or cord disruption) has the poorest prognosis with typically complete SCI and minimal recovery.")
B.Ir=s(["Epidural hematomas are more common in children than adults","Children have shorter concussion recovery times (7 days vs. 14 days)","Children have higher brain water content and are more susceptible to diffuse injury","Post-traumatic epilepsy is more common after pediatric TBI than adult TBI"],t.s)
B.OS=new A.t("Which statement correctly distinguishes pediatric from adult TBI?",B.Ir,2,"Children have higher brain water content, less myelin, and are more susceptible to diffuse cerebral swelling than adults. Epidural hematomas are actually LESS common in children. Concussion recovery is LONGER in children (2-4 weeks vs. 10-14 days in adults). Late post-traumatic epilepsy rates are lower in children than adults for equivalent severity.")
B.G1=s(["1-2%","7-10%","25-30%","50%"],t.s)
B.OU=new A.t("According to population-based data, the risk of post-traumatic epilepsy after severe TBI is approximately:",B.G1,1,"The Annegers et al. study established PTE risk by severity: mild TBI ~1-2%, moderate ~1.6%, and severe ~7-10%. Risk is elevated for more than 10 years after severe TBI. Penetrating injuries carry the highest risk at up to 50%. Seizure prophylaxis in the first 7 days reduces early seizures but does NOT prevent late PTE.")
B.J0=s(["No imaging is necessary","Lateral flexion-extension cervical spine radiographs","MRI of the cervical spine with contrast","CT angiogram of the vertebral arteries"],t.s)
B.Ok=new A.t("An 8-year-old with Down syndrome wants to participate in Special Olympics gymnastics. What cervical spine evaluation is required?",B.J0,1,"Special Olympics requires lateral cervical spine radiographs (flexion, extension, and neutral views) before participation in high-risk sports including gymnastics, diving, and butterfly stroke. Athletes with an atlantodental interval > 4.5 mm or signs of myelopathy are restricted. AAI occurs in 10-30% of Down syndrome but is symptomatic in only 1-2%.")
B.Gr=s(["C5-C6","C4-C5","C2-C3","C7-T1"],t.s)
B.R1=new A.t("In a child younger than 8 years, the fulcrum of cervical spine motion is located at which level?",B.Gr,2,"The cervical spine fulcrum in young children is at C2-C3, compared to C5-C6 in adults. This higher fulcrum, combined with the proportionally large head, ligamentous laxity, and immature musculature, predisposes children under 8 to upper cervical (C1-C4) injuries. Adult-type biomechanics develop by approximately age 8-10.")
B.JW=s(["10-20%","50-60%","75-80%","97-100%"],t.s)
B.Pl=new A.t("What percentage of children who sustain SCI before age 10 will develop scoliosis?",B.JW,3,"Nearly 100% of children who sustain SCI before age 10 develop neuromuscular scoliosis. Risk is inversely proportional to age at injury: before age 10 = 97-100%, ages 10-15 = 50-80%, after skeletal maturity = 5-10%. This mandates lifelong spinal surveillance. Bracing can slow progression but generally cannot prevent surgical fusion.")
B.In=s(["1 cm","2 cm","5 cm","10 cm"],t.s)
B.QC=new A.t("The pediatric spinal column can stretch up to approximately how far without structural disruption, compared to the spinal cord tolerance of only about 6 mm?",B.In,2,"The pediatric spinal column can stretch up to 5 cm (2 inches) without structural disruption, while the spinal cord tolerates only approximately 6 mm (0.25 inches) of distraction. This discrepancy in elasticity is the fundamental biomechanical basis for SCIWORA, which accounts for up to 30-60% of SCIs in young children.")
B.HZ=s(["1 week","2 weeks","4 weeks","3 months"],t.s)
B.O3=new A.t("According to the Amsterdam 2022 consensus, persistent post-concussion symptoms in children are defined as symptoms lasting beyond:",B.HZ,2,'Persistent post-concussion symptoms are defined as > 4 weeks in children (vs. > 2 weeks in adults). The older term "post-concussion syndrome" has been replaced. Children and adolescents typically take 2-4 weeks to recover from concussion, which is longer than the 10-14 day average in adults.')
B.Gt=s(["Dyskinetic","Ataxic","Spastic","Mixed"],t.s)
B.Oi=new A.t("What is the most common type of cerebral palsy?",B.Gt,2,"Spastic CP accounts for 70-80% of all cases. It is characterized by upper motor neuron pattern with velocity-dependent increase in tone.")
B.G7=s(["Kernicterus","Periventricular leukomalacia (PVL)","MCA infarction","Postnatal meningitis"],t.s)
B.OR=new A.t("Spastic diplegia is most commonly associated with which etiology?",B.G7,1,"Spastic diplegia (Little disease) is the most common type in premature infants and is associated with periventricular leukomalacia (PVL) from ischemia of the periventricular germinal matrix.")
B.HA=s(["Walks without limitations","Walks with limitations","Walks with a handheld mobility device","Uses powered mobility"],t.s)
B.R5=new A.t("GMFCS Level III indicates a child who:",B.HA,2,"GMFCS: I = walks without limitations, II = walks with limitations, III = walks with handheld mobility device (walker/crutches), IV = self-mobility limited/uses powered wheelchair, V = transported in manual wheelchair.")
B.Hi=s(["Level III uses a manual wheelchair; Level IV uses a power wheelchair","Level III walks with a handheld device; Level IV is primarily wheelchair-bound and may stand for transfers","Level III walks without limitations; Level IV walks with limitations","Level III has full trunk control; Level IV has no trunk control"],t.s)
B.PI=new A.t("The key distinction between GMFCS Level III and GMFCS Level IV is:",B.Hi,1,'GMFCS III walks with a handheld mobility device (walker/crutches) indoors and uses wheeled mobility for community distances. GMFCS IV has limited self-mobility and is primarily wheelchair-bound, though may stand for transfers with assistance. This is the "walking vs. wheelchair" dividing line.')
B.Kd=s(["Abnormal MRI findings","Low HINE score","Absent fidgety movements on General Movements Assessment","Persistent ATNR"],t.s)
B.OH=new A.t("According to the Novak 2017 guideline, what is the single best early predictor of cerebral palsy at 3-5 months corrected age?",B.Kd,2,"Absent fidgety movements on the General Movements Assessment (GMA) at 3-5 months corrected age is the single best predictor of CP (98% sensitivity). The Novak 2017 guideline recommends combining GMA + MRI + HINE for maximum accuracy (>97% sensitivity, >99% specificity), enabling diagnosis before 5 months corrected age.")
B.J9=s(["10%","25%","50%","90%"],t.s)
B.Qm=new A.t("What is the approximate prevalence of intellectual disability among all individuals with cerebral palsy?",B.J9,2,"Approximately 50% of individuals with CP have intellectual disability (range 30-65% depending on CP type). ID is highest in spastic quadriplegia. Other key associated conditions include epilepsy (25-45%), chronic pain (50-75%), feeding difficulties (40-90% in severe CP), and visual impairment (20-40%).")
B.Ik=s(["Spastic diplegia and ataxic CP","Spastic hemiplegia and spastic quadriplegia","Dyskinetic CP and ataxic CP","Ataxic CP only"],t.s)
B.QI=new A.t("Epilepsy in cerebral palsy is most common in which subtypes?",B.Ik,1,"Epilepsy occurs in 25-45% of individuals with CP and is most common in spastic hemiplegia (focal cortical lesions) and spastic quadriplegia (extensive brain injury). It is less common in spastic diplegia (predominantly white matter injury) and ataxic CP.")
B.I3=s(["Intrathecal baclofen overdose","Intrathecal baclofen withdrawal","Neuroleptic malignant syndrome from a new medication","Sepsis from pump infection"],t.s)
B.Os=new A.t("A child with a baclofen pump presents with fever, tachycardia, hypertension, and severe rebound spasticity. This presentation is most consistent with:",B.I3,1,"ITB withdrawal presents with HYPER symptoms: fever, tachycardia, hypertension, diaphoresis, and rebound spasticity. It can progress to rhabdomyolysis, seizures, multi-organ failure, and death. ITB overdose presents with HYPO symptoms: hypotension, hypothermia, hypotonia, and respiratory depression. ITB withdrawal is a medical emergency requiring immediate restoration of baclofen delivery.")
B.EL=s(["Administer IV fluids and vasopressors","Secure the airway and provide ventilatory support; turn off/empty the pump","Give naloxone for presumed opioid toxicity","Increase the pump infusion rate"],t.s)
B.OB=new A.t("A child with an intrathecal baclofen pump presents with hypotension, hypothermia, flaccidity, and respiratory depression. The FIRST management step is:",B.EL,1,"ITB overdose causes HYPO symptoms (hypotension, hypothermia, hypotonia, respiratory depression, coma). Management is primarily supportive: secure the airway, provide ventilatory support, and turn off or empty the pump. CSF withdrawal may be considered if feasible. This presentation should not be confused with ITB withdrawal, which produces HYPER symptoms.")
B.Fi=s(["A 5-year-old with dyskinetic CP at GMFCS IV","A 6-year-old with spastic diplegia at GMFCS III with PVL on MRI and good selective motor control","A 12-year-old with spastic quadriplegia and fixed knee contractures","A 4-year-old with ataxic CP at GMFCS II"],t.s)
B.Ot=new A.t("Which of the following is the ideal candidate for selective dorsal rhizotomy (SDR)?",B.Fi,1,"The ideal SDR candidate has: age 3-8 years, pure spastic diplegia (no dystonia/athetosis), GMFCS II-III, PVL on MRI, adequate underlying voluntary strength, good selective motor control, no fixed contractures, and a motivated family. SDR does not work for dystonia or athetosis and is not appropriate for GMFCS IV-V.")
B.EI=s(["10%","30%","50%","70%"],t.s)
B.QS=new A.t('In cerebral palsy hip surveillance, a migration percentage (Reimers index) above what threshold indicates the hip is "at risk" and warrants intervention?',B.EI,1,"Migration percentage thresholds: <30% = normal (observe), 30-40% = at risk (botulinum toxin to adductors + hip abduction orthosis), 40-50% = subluxation (soft tissue surgery), >50% = significant subluxation (bony reconstruction with VDRO +/- pelvic osteotomy), >90-100% = dislocation (salvage procedures if symptomatic).")
B.Ji=s(["100 U total","200 U total","400 U total or 12-16 U/kg","600 U total or 20 U/kg"],t.s)
B.Q0=new A.t("What is the maximum recommended total body dose of onabotulinumtoxinA (Botox) for pediatric spasticity?",B.Ji,2,"OnabotulinumtoxinA dosing for pediatric spasticity: 1-6 U/kg per individual muscle, with a maximum total body dose of 400 U or 12-16 U/kg (whichever is less). Onset is 24-72 hours, peak effect at 2-6 weeks, and duration 3-6 months. Minimum re-injection interval is 3 months. It is used off-label in pediatrics.")
B.HM=s(["Rolling by 6 months","Independent sitting by age 2 years","Pulling to stand by 12 months","Crawling by 9 months"],t.s)
B.Ou=new A.t("Which early motor milestone in CP is most predictive of ambulatory prognosis?",B.HM,1,"Independent sitting by age 2 years is a strong predictor of ambulatory potential. Approximately 60% of all individuals with CP are ambulatory (GMFCS I-III). GMFCS level is generally stable after age 2, and motor growth curves can predict peak gross motor function and subsequent trajectory.")
B.EU=s(["Normal early lateralization","Spastic hemiplegia (unilateral CP)","Ataxic CP","Brachial plexus injury that has resolved"],t.s)
B.Qv=new A.t("Hand preference before age 12 months in an infant should raise suspicion for:",B.EU,1,"Hand preference before 12 months is NOT normal and should raise suspicion for spastic hemiplegia (unilateral CP). Other early signs prompting referral for the GMA-MRI-HINE diagnostic battery include: persistent hand fisting beyond 4 months, head lag beyond 4 months, absent or asymmetric reaching by 5 months, and any motor milestone regression.")
B.HF=s(["Age 2-3 years","Age 6-8 years","Age 12-14 years","Peak motor function continues to improve throughout life"],t.s)
B.RA=new A.t("At what age do children at GMFCS Level III typically reach peak gross motor function, after which decline is expected?",B.HF,1,"Motor development trajectories differ by GMFCS level. GMFCS III peaks around age 6-8, then declines in adolescence. GMFCS IV peaks around age 5-7, GMFCS V around age 3-5. This decline is due to increasing body mass, loss of flexibility, and reduced activity -- not progression of the brain lesion. Families should receive anticipatory guidance about expected decline.")
B.IV=s(["15%","40%","70%","90%"],t.s)
B.R_=new A.t("What is the approximate risk of hip displacement in a child at GMFCS Level V?",B.IV,3,"Hip displacement risk increases dramatically with GMFCS level: I = ~1%, II = ~15%, III = ~40%, IV = ~70%, V = ~90%. The Swedish CPUP surveillance program demonstrated that systematic hip monitoring with timely intervention reduced the rate of hip dislocation requiring surgery from approximately 8% to nearly 0%.")
B.FO=s(["Lower extremity fibers pass through the basal ganglia","Lower extremity fibers are less myelinated at birth","Lower extremity fibers run closest to the lateral ventricles","Lower extremity fibers cross at a lower level in the brainstem"],t.s)
B.PG=new A.t("Periventricular leukomalacia (PVL) in preterm infants preferentially damages corticospinal fibers to the lower extremities because:",B.FO,2,"Descending corticospinal fibers from the leg representation area of the motor cortex run closest to the lateral ventricles, making them the most vulnerable to PVL. This anatomical relationship explains why PVL characteristically produces spastic diplegia (legs more affected than arms). PVL is the most common neuropathology in preterm CP.")
B.IQ=s(["Gastrocnemius spasticity alone","Overlengthening of the Achilles tendon, adolescent growth, or isolated hamstring lengthening","Tibialis anterior weakness","Hip adductor contracture"],t.s)
B.PB=new A.t("Crouch gait in a teenager with spastic diplegic CP is MOST commonly caused by:",B.IQ,1,"Crouch gait (excessive dorsiflexion, knee flexion, hip flexion) is often iatrogenic from overlengthening of the Achilles tendon or isolated hamstring lengthening. It also develops naturally during adolescent growth in GMFCS III-IV. Crouch gait is treated with a ground reaction AFO (GRAFO) and may require patellar tendon advancement. It leads to patella alta and patellofemoral pain if untreated.")
B.EV=s(["10%","30%","60%","90%"],t.s)
B.PF=new A.t("What percentage of children with myelomeningocele require a VP shunt for hydrocephalus?",B.EV,3,"Approximately 90% of children with myelomeningocele develop hydrocephalus requiring VP shunt placement. Arnold-Chiari II malformation is present in 80-90%.")
B.JZ=s(["Use a wheelchair full-time","Ambulate with KAFOs","Ambulate with AFOs as a community ambulator","Ambulate without orthoses"],t.s)
B.O8=new A.t("A child with a motor level of L4 in spina bifida would be expected to:",B.JZ,2,"L4 motor level = tibialis anterior present (dorsiflexion). Expected to be a community ambulator with AFOs. L3 = household ambulator with KAFOs. L5 = community ambulator with AFOs. S1-S2 = may need no orthosis.")
B.Iu=s(["0.4 mg","1 mg","2 mg","4 mg"],t.s)
B.PE=new A.t("The recommended daily folic acid supplementation for a woman with a prior pregnancy affected by a neural tube defect is:",B.Iu,3,"All women of childbearing age should take 0.4 mg/day of folic acid. Women with a prior NTD pregnancy should take 4 mg/day, which reduces recurrence risk by 50-70%.")
B.H4=s(["Significantly improved cognitive (Bayley MDI) scores","Reduction in VP shunt rate from 82% to 40%","Elimination of Chiari II malformation in all cases","No significant difference in any outcome"],t.s)
B.R3=new A.t("In the MOMS trial, prenatal repair of myelomeningocele compared to postnatal repair resulted in which primary outcome?",B.H4,1,"The MOMS trial (NEJM, 2011) showed three key results: (1) VP shunt rate cut in half (40% prenatal vs. 82% postnatal), (2) motor function significantly better (42% walking independently vs. 21%), and (3) cognitive outcomes were NOT different between groups. Trade-offs include increased preterm birth (mean 34.1 vs. 37.3 weeks) and maternal morbidity.")
B.JR=s(["Tibialis anterior (ankle dorsiflexion)","Quadriceps (knee extension)","Gastrocnemius/soleus (plantarflexion)","Gluteus medius (hip abduction)"],t.s)
B.Re=new A.t("A child with spina bifida at the L3 motor level has which key muscle group intact?",B.JR,1,'L3 = quadriceps (knee extension). This is critical to know: L3 provides household/limited community ambulation with KAFOs. L4 = tibialis anterior (dorsiflexion), the classic "AFO level" for community ambulation. L5 = lateral hamstrings/peroneals/partial gluteus medius. S1 = gastrocnemius/soleus. Quadriceps function is the key determinant of ambulation potential.')
B.HD=s(["20-30%","50-60%","70-80%","95-100%"],t.s)
B.Qw=new A.t("Arnold-Chiari II malformation is associated with myelomeningocele in approximately what percentage of cases?",B.HD,3,"Chiari II is present in approximately 95-100% of patients with myelomeningocele. It involves downward displacement of the cerebellar tonsils, vermis, brainstem, and fourth ventricle through the foramen magnum. Chiari II is distinct from Chiari I (tonsillar herniation only, NOT associated with myelomeningocele). Only 5-10% require surgical decompression.")
B.G6=s(["Wheat proteins","Latex proteins","Nickel","Egg albumin"],t.s)
B.OL=new A.t("A child with myelomeningocele reports oral tingling after eating bananas and avocados. This is most likely due to cross-reactivity with:",B.G6,1,"Latex allergy occurs in 30-65% of spina bifida patients (vs. ~1% general population) due to repeated early latex exposure. Cross-reactive foods share structural protein homology with latex. The BACK mnemonic: Banana, Avocado, Chestnut, Kiwi. Latex-free precautions from birth are now standard of care for ALL spina bifida patients.")
B.JI=s(["0.1 mg","0.4 mg","1.0 mg","4.0 mg"],t.s)
B.PQ=new A.t("A woman with NO prior neural tube defect-affected pregnancy should take what daily dose of folic acid for NTD prevention?",B.JI,1,"All women of childbearing age should take 0.4 mg (400 mcg) folic acid daily for primary NTD prevention. Women with a prior NTD-affected pregnancy require 4 mg (4,000 mcg) daily, started 1-3 months before conception through the first trimester. This high dose reduces NTD recurrence by 50-70%. Folic acid must begin before conception because the neural tube closes by day 28.")
B.Gd=s(["20 cm H2O","40 cm H2O","60 cm H2O","80 cm H2O"],t.s)
B.NT=new A.t("A detrusor leak point pressure above what threshold indicates high risk for upper urinary tract deterioration in neurogenic bladder?",B.Gd,1,"A detrusor leak point pressure > 40 cm H2O (the McGuire threshold) indicates high risk for upper tract damage including vesicoureteral reflux, hydronephrosis, and renal failure. The primary goal of neurogenic bladder management is renal preservation through maintenance of low intravesical pressures. Urodynamics is the gold standard evaluation.")
B.GX=s(["Progressive scoliosis","Change in urodynamic pattern","Upper extremity weakness","Headache with Valsalva"],t.s)
B.Qe=new A.t("Which of the following is the EARLIEST detectable sign of symptomatic tethered cord in a child with myelomeningocele?",B.GX,1,"Urodynamic changes (new detrusor overactivity, decreased compliance, increased post-void residuals) may be the earliest detectable sign of tethered cord. Tethered cord in MMC is a CLINICAL diagnosis -- MRI shows tethering in virtually all post-repair patients, so the decision to operate is driven by progressive symptoms, not imaging alone. Always evaluate VP shunt function first.")
B.HG=s(["2-3 years","5-7 years","10-12 years","14-16 years"],t.s)
B.QA=new A.t("At what age should children with spina bifida typically begin learning self-catheterization?",B.HG,1,"Self-catheterization training typically begins at age 5-7 years with a goal of independence by age 8-10. Clean intermittent catheterization (CIC) is the cornerstone of neurogenic bladder management and is performed every 3-4 hours. CIC revolutionized spina bifida care and dramatically reduced renal morbidity, which was previously the leading cause of death.")
B.Jd=s(["30%","50%","75%","96%"],t.s)
B.OI=new A.t("What percentage of VP shunts in children with myelomeningocele will malfunction and require at least one revision?",B.Jd,3,"96% of shunted patients need at least one revision, and 86% need two or more. The most common complication is obstruction, with 40-50% malfunctioning within the first 2 years. The most common shunt infection organism is Staphylococcus epidermidis. ANY acute neurological change in a shunted patient should be treated as shunt malfunction until proven otherwise.")
B.Gs=s(["Levetiracetam","Lamotrigine","Carbamazepine","Valproic acid"],t.s)
B.Rp=new A.t("Which antiepileptic drug carries the highest risk of neural tube defects and should be avoided in women of childbearing potential?",B.Gs,3,"Valproic acid is the most teratogenic commonly used antiepileptic drug for NTDs, with a 1-2% NTD risk (10-20x baseline). Its mechanism involves inhibition of folate metabolism and histone deacetylase activity. Women on valproic acid should receive high-dose folic acid supplementation and counseling about alternative medications. Carbamazepine carries a 0.5-1% NTD risk.")
B.IP=s(["10%","21%","42%","75%"],t.s)
B.Ro=new A.t("In the MOMS trial, what percentage of children in the prenatal repair group were walking independently at 30 months?",B.IP,2,"42% of children in the prenatal repair group were walking independently at 30 months vs. 21% in the postnatal group. At school-age follow-up (MOMS2), community walking was 45% prenatal vs. 24% postnatal. Importantly, cognitive outcomes (Bayley MDI) were similar between groups at both timepoints.")
B.Ka=s(["Speech therapy evaluation only","Reassurance and observation","Urgent posterior fossa decompression for symptomatic Chiari II","Oral steroids for 2 weeks"],t.s)
B.Qa=new A.t("A 3-month-old with myelomeningocele presents with new-onset stridor and feeding difficulties. After confirming VP shunt function, the next step is:",B.Ka,2,"In infants with myelomeningocele, new-onset stridor (from bilateral vocal cord paralysis) and feeding difficulties indicate symptomatic Chiari II brainstem compression. This carries 15-35% mortality if symptomatic in infancy. CRITICAL RULE: Always check VP shunt function FIRST, as shunt malfunction can mimic Chiari II symptoms. If shunt is functioning, urgent posterior fossa decompression is indicated.")
B.GK=s(["Equinovarus (clubfoot)","Calcaneus deformity","Pes planus (flat foot)","Cavovarus"],t.s)
B.Rx=new A.t("A child with spina bifida at the L4-L5 motor level is most likely to develop which foot deformity?",B.GK,1,"L4-L5 levels develop calcaneus deformity because dorsiflexors (tibialis anterior at L4, peroneals at L5) are present without opposing plantarflexors (gastrocnemius/soleus at S1). S1 level develops cavovarus (intrinsic minus foot). This muscle imbalance pattern determines the orthopedic deformity at each level.")
B.J8=s(["Spina bifida occulta","Lipomyelomeningocele","Myelomeningocele (open NTD)","All forms of spina bifida"],t.s)
B.QY=new A.t("Maternal serum alpha-fetoprotein (MSAFP) is elevated in which type of spina bifida?",B.J8,2,"MSAFP is elevated only in OPEN neural tube defects (myelomeningocele, anencephaly) where neural tissue is exposed to amniotic fluid. Closed spinal dysraphisms (lipomyelomeningocele, spina bifida occulta) do NOT elevate MSAFP because there is no exposed neural tissue. This is a frequently tested distinction.")
B.GV=s(["Bladder","Sigmoid colon","Cecum","Ileum"],t.s)
B.P6=new A.t("The Malone antegrade continence enema (MACE) procedure involves creation of a catheterizable channel from the skin surface to which structure?",B.GV,2,"The MACE procedure creates an appendicostomy or cecostomy providing access to the cecum for antegrade enema administration. Enema solution instilled into the cecum produces predictable, scheduled bowel evacuation, achieving social continence in approximately 85% of patients. This is distinct from the Mitrofanoff procedure, which creates a catheterizable channel to the bladder.")
B.Gw=s(["Emerin","Dystrophin","Frataxin","SMN1"],t.s)
B.PS=new A.t("Duchenne muscular dystrophy is caused by a mutation affecting which protein?",B.Gw,1,"DMD is caused by mutations in the dystrophin gene on Xp21, resulting in absent or near-absent (<3%) dystrophin protein. Becker MD has the same gene but produces reduced/abnormal dystrophin.")
B.Jj=s(["Walks independently then loses ability","Sits independently but never stands","Never achieves independent sitting","Has normal motor development until age 2"],t.s)
B.QN=new A.t("SMA Type I (Werdnig-Hoffmann disease) is characterized by onset before 6 months and the child:",B.Jj,2,"SMA types by motor milestone: Type I = never sits (onset <6 months), Type II = sits but never stands (onset 6-18 months), Type III = stands/walks then loses (onset >18 months). Mnemonic: 1-2-3 = None-Sit-Stand.")
B.J3=s(["C5-C6","C7","C8-T1","C5-T1"],t.s)
B.OW=new A.t("Erb-Duchenne palsy involves injury to which nerve roots?",B.J3,0,"Erb palsy (C5-C6) presents with waiter tip position: adducted/internally rotated shoulder, extended elbow, pronated forearm. Klumpke palsy (C8-T1) presents with claw hand \xb1 Horner syndrome.")
B.Jl=s(["5q13","Xp21.2","17p11.2","9q21"],t.s)
B.Rn=new A.t("The dystrophin gene responsible for Duchenne muscular dystrophy is located at:",B.Jl,1,"The dystrophin gene is located at Xp21.2 on the X chromosome. It is the largest known human gene (~2.4 megabases, 79 exons). In DMD, out-of-frame mutations produce absent or near-absent (<3%) dystrophin protein. In BMD, in-frame mutations produce a shortened but partially functional dystrophin. Approximately 30% of DMD cases are de novo mutations.")
B.Ig=s(["Distal upper extremity weakness","Proximal pelvic girdle weakness","Cerebellar ataxia","Spinal cord compression"],t.s)
B.OM=new A.t("The Gower sign is characteristic of DMD but is NOT disease-specific. It indicates:",B.Ig,1,'The Gower sign is a compensatory maneuver where the child uses hands to "climb up" the thighs when rising from the floor, reflecting proximal hip and knee extensor weakness. While characteristic of DMD, it is not specific and can be seen in any condition causing proximal lower extremity weakness including SMA type III, limb-girdle muscular dystrophies, and inflammatory myopathies.')
B.Hz=s(["Age 4-6","Age 9-13","Age 16-18","Age 20-25"],t.s)
B.O_=new A.t("Without corticosteroid treatment, loss of independent ambulation in DMD typically occurs at what age?",B.Hz,1,"Loss of ambulation in DMD typically occurs between ages 9 and 13 without treatment. Corticosteroid therapy extends the ambulatory period by 2-5 years. After ambulation loss, progressive scoliosis develops in > 90%. The clinical threshold distinguishing DMD from BMD is loss of ambulation before vs. after age 16.")
B.IW=s(["Never achieves independent sitting","Sits independently but never walks","Walks independently but may later lose ambulation","Normal motor development with mild weakness"],t.s)
B.Oq=new A.t("A child with SMA Type II (Dubowitz disease) achieves which maximum motor milestone?",B.IW,1,"SMA classification by maximum milestone: Type I (Werdnig-Hoffmann) = never sits (onset <6 months), Type II (Dubowitz) = sits but never walks (onset 6-18 months), Type III (Kugelberg-Welander) = walks independently but may lose ability (onset >18 months). Mnemonic: 1-2-3 = None-Sit-Stand. SMN2 copy number inversely correlates with severity.")
B.Jk=s(["Nusinersen (Spinraza)","Onasemnogene abeparvovec (Zolgensma)","Risdiplam (Evrysdi)","Eteplirsen (Exondys 51)"],t.s)
B.Rs=new A.t("Which SMA disease-modifying therapy is administered as a single one-time intravenous infusion?",B.Jk,1,"Onasemnogene abeparvovec (Zolgensma) is a one-time IV AAV9 gene replacement therapy delivering a functional SMN1 gene, approved for SMA patients < 2 years. Nusinersen (Spinraza) is an intrathecal antisense oligonucleotide given with loading doses then every 4 months. Risdiplam (Evrysdi) is a daily oral SMN2 splicing modifier. Eteplirsen is for DMD, not SMA.")
B.JN=s(["FXN gene GAA trinucleotide repeat on chromosome 9","PMP22 gene duplication on chromosome 17p11.2","SMN1 deletion on chromosome 5q13","Dystrophin gene mutation on Xp21"],t.s)
B.PN=new A.t("CMT1A, the most common form of Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease, is caused by:",B.JN,1,'CMT1A is caused by a 1.5-megabase duplication on chromosome 17p11.2 containing the PMP22 (peripheral myelin protein 22) gene. It is autosomal dominant and accounts for ~50% of all CMT. It is a demyelinating neuropathy with NCV < 38 m/s and "onion bulb" formations on nerve biopsy from repeated demyelination-remyelination cycles.')
B.Gq=s(["Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease","Friedreich ataxia","Spinal muscular atrophy","Multiple sclerosis"],t.s)
B.Qh=new A.t("The combination of areflexia AND extensor plantar responses (Babinski sign) in a young patient with progressive ataxia is most suggestive of:",B.Gq,1,"The co-existence of areflexia (LMN finding from dorsal root ganglion/peripheral nerve involvement) and Babinski sign (UMN finding from corticospinal tract degeneration) in a young patient with progressive ataxia is classic for Friedreich ataxia. FRDA is autosomal recessive, caused by GAA trinucleotide repeat expansion in the FXN (frataxin) gene on chromosome 9q21.")
B.Jw=s(["Absent dystrophin, causing the severe DMD phenotype","Truncated but partially functional dystrophin, causing the milder BMD phenotype","Absent emerin, causing Emery-Dreifuss muscular dystrophy","Overexpression of dystrophin, causing the DMD phenotype"],t.s)
B.OG=new A.t("The reading frame hypothesis distinguishes DMD from BMD. In-frame mutations produce:",B.Jw,1,"The reading frame hypothesis (Monaco et al., 1988): out-of-frame mutations disrupt the reading frame, produce nonfunctional dystrophin, and cause severe DMD. In-frame mutations preserve the reading frame, produce shortened but partially functional dystrophin, and cause milder BMD. This rule holds in approximately 90-95% of cases. The clinical dividing line is ambulation loss before (DMD) vs. after (BMD) age 16.")
B.JJ=s(["Rocuronium","Vecuronium","Succinylcholine","Cisatracurium"],t.s)
B.O6=new A.t("Which neuromuscular blocking agent is ABSOLUTELY contraindicated in Duchenne muscular dystrophy?",B.JJ,2,"Succinylcholine is absolutely contraindicated in DMD and all dystrophinopathies. The unstable sarcolemma leads to massive potassium release with depolarization, causing fatal hyperkalemia and rhabdomyolysis. Volatile halogenated anesthetics also carry risk. Total intravenous anesthesia (TIVA) is the recommended approach. This also applies to patients with central core disease (RYR1 mutations) due to malignant hyperthermia risk.")
B.EQ=s(["Normal (50-200 IU/L)","500-1,000 IU/L","10,000-50,000 IU/L","Over 100,000 IU/L"],t.s)
B.Qi=new A.t("CK levels in a boy with Duchenne muscular dystrophy are typically in what range?",B.EQ,2,"CK is markedly elevated in DMD at 10,000-50,000 IU/L (50-100x normal), present from birth even before clinical symptoms appear. CK is the most sensitive initial screening test for DMD. Values peak in early childhood and gradually decline as muscle mass is lost and replaced by fibrotic/adipose tissue. BMD has lower values (2,000-20,000 IU/L).")
B.Ho=s(["At diagnosis","Age 6","Age 10 or at first sign of cardiac dysfunction","Only after confirmed heart failure"],t.s)
B.NV=new A.t("According to the Birnkrant 2018 DMD care considerations, prophylactic ACE inhibitor or ARB therapy is recommended by what age?",B.Ho,2,"The Birnkrant 2018 guidelines recommend prophylactic ACE inhibitor or ARB therapy by age 10 or at the first sign of cardiac dysfunction. Baseline cardiac evaluation (ECG + echo or cardiac MRI) should occur at diagnosis or by age 6, then every 2 years until age 10, then annually. Cardiac MRI is superior to echocardiography for detecting early posterolateral LV fibrosis.")
B.Ht=s(["Oral daily","Subcutaneous injection","Intrathecal injection","Intravenous infusion"],t.s)
B.O9=new A.t("Nusinersen (Spinraza) for spinal muscular atrophy is administered via which route?",B.Ht,2,"Nusinersen is an antisense oligonucleotide administered via intrathecal injection with a loading schedule (days 1, 14, 28, 63) then maintenance every 4 months. It modifies SMN2 pre-mRNA splicing to increase full-length SMN protein production. Approved in December 2016 for all SMA types and ages. Risdiplam is the oral alternative; onasemnogene is IV gene therapy.")
B.FY=s(["25 m/s","38 m/s","50 m/s","60 m/s"],t.s)
B.Q3=new A.t("The electrophysiological threshold that distinguishes demyelinating (CMT1) from axonal (CMT2) Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease is a median motor nerve conduction velocity of:",B.FY,1,"A median motor NCV of 38 m/s is the threshold: demyelinating CMT (CMT1) has NCV < 38 m/s (often 15-30 m/s), while axonal CMT (CMT2) has NCV > 38 m/s with reduced CMAP amplitudes. CMT1A (PMP22 duplication) shows onion bulb formations on nerve biopsy. CMTX1 has intermediate NCVs (25-40 m/s in males).")
B.GT=s(["Neuroleptic malignant syndrome","Serotonin syndrome","Malignant hyperthermia","Succinylcholine-induced bradycardia"],t.s)
B.Qu=new A.t("Central core disease caused by RYR1 mutations is uniquely associated with susceptibility to:",B.GT,2,"Central core disease is caused by RYR1 (ryanodine receptor 1) mutations and carries a unique risk of malignant hyperthermia. Both volatile halogenated anesthetics and succinylcholine are absolutely contraindicated. Trigger-free anesthesia with dantrolene available is required. All family members carrying RYR1 mutations should be treated as MH-susceptible.")
B.EO=s(["Dystrophin","Frataxin","Myotubularin","Emerin"],t.s)
B.Qd=new A.t("Friedreich ataxia is caused by a GAA trinucleotide repeat expansion in the FXN gene encoding which mitochondrial protein?",B.EO,1,"Friedreich ataxia is autosomal recessive, caused by GAA repeat expansion in the FXN gene on chromosome 9q21.11 encoding frataxin, a mitochondrial protein involved in iron-sulfur cluster assembly. 96% of patients are homozygous for the GAA expansion (normal 5-33 repeats; pathogenic 66-1700+ repeats). Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy is the most common cause of death (~60%).")
B.EZ=s(["Baclofen","Diazepam","Dantrolene","Tizanidine"],t.s)
B.OJ=new A.t("Which spasticity medication acts peripherally at the muscle rather than centrally?",B.EZ,2,"Dantrolene acts peripherally by inhibiting calcium release from the sarcoplasmic reticulum in skeletal muscle. Baclofen (GABA-B agonist), diazepam (GABA-A), and tizanidine (alpha-2 agonist) all act centrally.")
B.JA=s(["Stevens-Johnson syndrome","Reye syndrome","Aplastic anemia","Hepatorenal syndrome"],t.s)
B.P4=new A.t("Which risk is associated with aspirin use in children during influenza or varicella infections?",B.JA,1,"Aspirin use during influenza or varicella infections in children is associated with Reye syndrome (acute encephalopathy and fatty liver degeneration). For this reason, aspirin is used less frequently in children.")
B.GO=s(["GABA-A receptor agonism at supraspinal levels","GABA-B receptor agonism with presynaptic inhibition at the spinal cord","Alpha-2 adrenergic agonism in the brainstem","Ryanodine receptor blockade at the sarcoplasmic reticulum"],t.s)
B.Oz=new A.t("Baclofen exerts its antispasticity effect primarily through which receptor mechanism?",B.GO,1,"Baclofen is a GABA-B receptor agonist that inhibits release of excitatory neurotransmitters (glutamate, aspartate) via presynaptic inhibition at the spinal cord level. Diazepam acts on GABA-A, tizanidine is an alpha-2 agonist, and dantrolene blocks ryanodine receptors.")
B.JS=s(["0.1 mg/kg/day","0.5 mg/kg/day","2 mg/kg/day","5 mg/kg/day"],t.s)
B.Rk=new A.t("What is the typical starting dose of oral baclofen in children for spasticity management?",B.JS,1,"Oral baclofen is initiated at 0.5 mg/kg/day divided into 2-3 doses, with weekly titration by 0.5 mg/kg/day. The target dose range is 1-2 mg/kg/day, with a maximum of approximately 60 mg/day in children.")
B.Gx=s(["Renal function tests monthly","Liver function tests at baseline and monthly for 6 months","Complete blood count weekly","Serum drug levels every 2 weeks"],t.s)
B.QR=new A.t("Which monitoring is most critical when prescribing dantrolene for spasticity in a child?",B.Gx,1,"Dantrolene carries a risk of idiosyncratic hepatotoxicity with case-fatality rates as high as 28%. LFTs must be monitored at baseline and monthly for the first 6 months. Risk factors include doses >400 mg/day, duration >60 days, and female sex. Dantrolene is contraindicated in active liver disease.")
B.G8=s(["Baclofen","Tizanidine","Dantrolene","Diazepam"],t.s)
B.Qf=new A.t("According to the 2010 AAN Practice Parameter, which oral antispasticity medication received Level A evidence for short-term spasticity reduction in children with cerebral palsy?",B.G8,3,"Diazepam (a GABA-A agonist) is the only oral antispasticity medication to receive Level A recommendation for short-term reduction of spasticity in children with CP. Baclofen, dantrolene, and tizanidine each received Level C evidence.")
B.HN=s(["Onset in minutes, peak at 1 week, duration 1-2 months","Onset in 24-72 hours, peak at ~2 weeks, duration 3-4 months","Onset in 1-2 weeks, peak at 6 weeks, duration 6-12 months","Onset in 24 hours, peak at 24 hours, duration 2 weeks"],t.s)
B.QV=new A.t("What is the expected timeline for botulinum toxin type A (BoNT-A) effect after injection for pediatric spasticity?",B.HN,1,"BoNT-A onset occurs within 24-72 hours, with peak effect at approximately 2 weeks and duration of 3-4 months on average (some patients experience benefit for up to 6-8 months). The minimum reinjection interval is 3 months.")
B.Hr=s(["6 U/kg (max 200 U total)","12-16 U/kg (max 400 U total)","30 U/kg (max 1000 U total)","20 U/kg (max 600 U total)"],t.s)
B.Og=new A.t("What is the maximum recommended dose per session for onabotulinumtoxinA (Botox) in pediatric spasticity management?",B.Hr,1,"OnabotulinumtoxinA (Botox) maximum dose is 12-16 U/kg per session with a total maximum of 400 U. AbobotulinumtoxinA (Dysport) has a maximum of 30 U/kg (max 1000 U total). The units are NOT interchangeable between formulations.")
B.Jr=s(["Motor nerves are easier to locate with ultrasound","Injection into mixed nerves risks painful dysesthesias from sensory fiber demyelination","Mixed nerves require higher concentrations of phenol","Motor nerve injection provides longer duration of effect"],t.s)
B.Py=new A.t("Why is phenol neurolysis ideally targeted to pure motor nerves rather than mixed sensorimotor nerves?",B.Jr,1,"Phenol causes Wallerian degeneration of targeted nerves. When mixed sensorimotor nerves are injected, demyelination of sensory fibers can produce severe, persistent dysesthetic pain that may be more disabling than the original spasticity. The obturator nerve motor branch is an ideal target because it is a pure motor nerve.")
B.ER=s(["Conclude the patient is not a candidate and cancel further testing","Repeat the trial at 75 mcg at least 24 hours later","Proceed directly to pump implantation at a higher daily dose","Switch to oral baclofen titration instead"],t.s)
B.Pt=new A.t("During an intrathecal baclofen (ITB) screening trial, a child receives 50 mcg with no clinical response. What is the appropriate next step?",B.ER,1,"The ITB trial protocol uses escalating bolus doses: 25-50 mcg initially, then 75 mcg, then 100 mcg, with each dose administered at least 24 hours apart. If no response occurs at 100 mcg, the patient is generally not considered a candidate for ITB pump implantation.")
B.IY=s(["Less than 1%","3-5%","10-22%","40-50%"],t.s)
B.Pw=new A.t("Abrupt intrathecal baclofen (ITB) withdrawal can be fatal. What is the reported case-fatality rate in published series?",B.IY,2,"ITB withdrawal carries a reported mortality of 10-22%. It presents with progressive hyperthermia, rigidity, and rhabdomyolysis resembling malignant hyperthermia. Management requires restoring intrathecal delivery as rapidly as possible, IV benzodiazepines, and ICU admission.")
B.H6=s(["8-year-old with mixed spastic-dystonic quadriplegia at GMFCS V","5-year-old with spastic diplegia at GMFCS II-III with pure spasticity and adequate underlying strength","2-year-old with hemiplegic CP at GMFCS I","12-year-old with spastic diplegia and 25-degree fixed knee contractures"],t.s)
B.PA=new A.t("Which patient profile is the ideal candidate for selective dorsal rhizotomy (SDR)?",B.H6,1,"The ideal SDR candidate is aged 3-8 years with spastic diplegia (GMFCS II-III), pure spasticity without dystonia, adequate voluntary motor control, and no significant fixed contractures. MRI showing PVL is the most favorable imaging pattern. SDR is irreversible.")
B.GU=s(["Self-reporting children aged 8 years and older","Children aged 2 months to 7 years and nonverbal/cognitively impaired patients of any age","Neonates only (0-28 days)","Adolescents aged 12-18 years"],t.s)
B.PC=new A.t("The FLACC pain scale is a behavioral observation tool validated for which patient population?",B.GU,1,"FLACC (Face, Legs, Activity, Cry, Consolability) is validated for ages 2 months to 7 years and for nonverbal or cognitively impaired patients of any age. Each category is scored 0-2 for a total of 0-10. The revised r-FLACC incorporates individualized pain descriptors for children with cognitive impairment.")
B.Ju=s(["Predominantly fixed contracture requiring surgical intervention","Predominantly spastic component likely responsive to BoNT-A or baclofen","Normal muscle tone with no intervention needed","Dystonic tone requiring deep brain stimulation"],t.s)
B.QZ=new A.t("On the Modified Tardieu Scale, R1 is 30 degrees and R2 is 60 degrees at the ankle. What does the R2-R1 difference of 30 degrees indicate?",B.Ju,1,"R1 is the angle of spastic catch during fast stretch; R2 is the full passive ROM during slow stretch. A large R2-R1 difference (30 degrees here) indicates a predominantly spastic component that is likely to respond to antispasticity treatments. A small R2-R1 difference indicates fixed contracture requiring mechanical or surgical intervention.")
B.HK=s(["At the time of diagnosis regardless of age","Ages 4-6 years when motor function plateaus or begins declining","After loss of ambulation around age 10-12","At age 2 with the first confirmed genetic diagnosis"],t.s)
B.QG=new A.t("At what age should corticosteroid therapy typically be initiated in boys with Duchenne muscular dystrophy?",B.HK,1,"Corticosteroids should be started when motor function plateaus or begins to decline, typically between ages 4 and 6. Starting too early exposes the child to side effects without clear benefit, while starting too late misses the window of maximum benefit. Prednisone (0.75 mg/kg/day) or deflazacort (0.9 mg/kg/day) are the standard regimens.")
B.Hw=s(["All three are given intravenously","Intrathecal, intravenous, and oral respectively","Subcutaneous, intrathecal, and oral respectively","Intravenous, intrathecal, and subcutaneous respectively"],t.s)
B.QF=new A.t("Which route of administration is used for each of the three FDA-approved SMA therapies: nusinersen, onasemnogene, and risdiplam?",B.Hw,1,"Nusinersen (Spinraza) is administered via intrathecal injection every 4 months after loading. Onasemnogene (Zolgensma) is a single intravenous infusion (one-time gene replacement). Risdiplam (Evrysdi) is a daily oral liquid. Each has a distinct mechanism: antisense oligonucleotide, AAV9 gene replacement, and small molecule SMN2 splicing modifier.")
B.EW=s(["Risk of fatal hepatotoxicity","Theoretical risk of damage to growth plate cartilage based on animal studies","Induction of premature epiphyseal closure","Suppression of the growth hormone axis"],t.s)
B.Ox=new A.t("Fluoroquinolone antibiotics are generally avoided in children under 18 years due to which concern?",B.EW,1,"Fluoroquinolones carry a theoretical risk of damaging growth plate cartilage based on animal studies showing arthropathy in juvenile animals, leading to an FDA black box warning. They are generally avoided in children <18 years. Corticosteroids suppress growth velocity via the GH/IGF-1 axis, and retinoids are associated with premature epiphyseal closure.")
B.GG=s(["12-18 months","3-4 years","5-6 years","8-10 years"],t.s)
B.Rr=new A.t("At what age are powered wheelchairs traditionally introduced for children who need them?",B.GG,2,"Powered wheelchairs are traditionally introduced at 5-6 years. However, with innovative technology, children as young as 12-18 months have been reported to successfully use power mobility. Cognitive skills of spatial relation and problem-solving are essential predictors.")
B.Kc=s(["Solid ankle-foot orthosis","Supramalleolar orthosis (SMO)","Ground reaction AFO (GRAFO)","Posterior leaf spring AFO"],t.s)
B.Ps=new A.t("A 3-year-old with Down syndrome presents with pes planovalgus and mild hypotonia but no equinus. Which orthosis is most appropriate?",B.Kc,1,"The SMO controls hindfoot valgus/varus by providing mediolateral stability at the subtalar joint. It does NOT control sagittal plane motion (dorsiflexion/plantarflexion). It is appropriate for pes planovalgus and mild hypotonia, commonly seen in Down syndrome. It is inappropriate for equinus or crouch gait.")
B.GD=s(["Drop-foot gait in swing phase","Hemiplegic gait with isolated dorsiflexor weakness","Crouch gait with excessive knee flexion in stance","Mild dynamic equinus in a community ambulator"],t.s)
B.Pj=new A.t("A posterior leaf spring (PLS) AFO is contraindicated in which gait pattern?",B.GD,2,"The PLS provides dorsiflexion assistance during swing to prevent foot drop but allows ankle dorsiflexion in stance. Because it cannot generate a knee extension moment, a child with crouch gait placed in a PLS will continue to collapse into the crouch pattern. The PLS is excellent for isolated foot drop.")
B.H0=s(["Allowing free dorsiflexion to strengthen quadriceps during stance","Directing the ground reaction force vector anterior to the knee, creating a passive knee extension moment","Blocking all ankle motion to eliminate third rocker","Providing dorsiflexion assist during swing phase only"],t.s)
B.QE=new A.t("The ground reaction AFO (GRAFO) corrects crouch gait by which biomechanical mechanism?",B.H0,1,"The GRAFO combines a solid AFO set in ~5 degrees dorsiflexion with an anterior tibial shell. These components together redirect the ground reaction force anterior to the knee joint center, generating a passive knee extension moment that compensates for weak quadriceps and counteracts excessive knee flexion. It is contraindicated with knee flexion contracture >10-15 degrees.")
B.FZ=s(["A child with crouch gait and weak quadriceps","A child with dynamic equinus and adequate quadriceps strength","A child with pes planovalgus and no sagittal plane deviation","A child with a knee flexion contracture of 20 degrees"],t.s)
B.NS=new A.t("A hinged AFO with plantarflexion stop is most appropriate for which patient?",B.FZ,1,"The hinged AFO blocks plantarflexion beyond neutral while allowing dorsiflexion in stance. It requires adequate quadriceps strength to control tibial advancement. If quadriceps are weak, the child collapses into crouch. Therefore, the hinged AFO is contraindicated in crouch gait and weak quadriceps.")
B.IT=s(["True equinus throughout the entire gait cycle","Drop foot in swing only with normal stance phase","Equinus with knee recurvatum and stiff knee in stance","Equinus with involvement of knee, hip, and pelvis"],t.s)
B.OD=new A.t("In the Winters-Gage-Hicks classification of hemiplegic gait, Type I involves which pattern?",B.IT,1,"Winters-Gage-Hicks classification: Type I = drop foot in swing only (PLS AFO), Type II = true equinus throughout gait cycle (hinged or solid AFO), Type III = equinus + knee involvement (solid AFO), Type IV = equinus + knee + hip + pelvis (solid AFO + consider multilevel surgery).")
B.Gn=s(["AFOs and forearm crutches for community ambulation","KAFOs for household and limited community ambulation","Wheelchair as primary mobility with standing frame for therapeutic standing","No orthosis needed; community ambulation expected"],t.s)
B.Q9=new A.t("A child with spina bifida at the thoracic motor level would most appropriately be managed with which mobility strategy?",B.Gn,2,"Thoracic-level spina bifida = no lower extremity motor function. Primary mobility is by wheelchair. Standing frames, parapodiums, or HKAFOs may be used for therapeutic standing/exercise ambulation. L4 level = AFOs with community ambulation. S1-S2 = SMO or no orthosis with community ambulation.")
B.HP=s(["6-8 hours per day","At least 12-13 hours per day; up to 16-23 hours for maximum benefit","Nighttime only (8-10 hours)","Full-time 24-hour wear"],t.s)
B.OK=new A.t("According to the BrAIST trial evidence, what is the recommended brace wear time to achieve maximum success in adolescent idiopathic scoliosis?",B.HP,1,"The BrAIST trial (Weinstein et al., 2013) demonstrated a clear dose-response: wearing the brace >12-13 hours/day achieved up to 90% success rates, while <6 hours/day was no better than observation. Recommended wear time is 16-23 hours/day. Bracing is indicated for curves 25-45 degrees with Risser 0-2.")
B.FG=s(["3-4 years","5-6 years","12-18 months","8-10 years"],t.s)
B.OA=new A.t("Current evidence supports introducing power mobility for children with significant mobility limitations as early as what age?",B.FG,2,"Current evidence supports introducing power mobility as early as 12-18 months. Self-initiated movement drives cognitive, social, and language development. Research has refuted two myths: there is no minimum cognitive level required, and early power mobility does NOT reduce motivation to walk.")
B.H_=s(["GMFCS (reclassify to a lower level)","GMFM-66 (evaluative measure that detects change)","Modified Ashworth Scale alone","Denver II developmental screening"],t.s)
B.Pq=new A.t("A child with CP receives botulinum toxin injections and intensive therapy. Which tool should be used to detect functional improvement?",B.H_,1,"The GMFCS is a classification system that is stable over time and does NOT change with intervention. The GMFM-66 is an evaluative measure designed to detect change in gross motor function over time. Reclassifying GMFCS level after intervention reflects a misunderstanding of the system.")
B.Ib=s(["0-100","18-126","0-88","1-7"],t.s)
B.O0=new A.t("The WeeFIM measures functional independence across 18 items. What is the score range?",B.Ib,1,"The WeeFIM has 18 items each scored on a 7-point ordinal scale (1 = total assistance to 7 = complete independence), giving a total range of 18 (total dependence) to 126 (complete independence). It covers 3 domains: self-care (8 items), mobility (5 items), and cognition (5 items).")
B.GF=s(["Classification level and ambulatory distance","Capability (what the child CAN do) and performance (how much help the child actually needs)","Spasticity severity and contracture degree","Cognitive function and motor function"],t.s)
B.NZ=new A.t("The PEDI (Pediatric Evaluation of Disability Inventory) uniquely measures which two constructs within the same instrument?",B.GF,1,"The PEDI measures both Functional Skills (capability \u2014 what the child CAN do, scored dichotomously) and Caregiver Assistance (performance \u2014 how much help is actually needed, scored on a 6-point scale) within the same instrument. This aligns with the ICF distinction between capacity and performance.")
B.JU=s(["No increase in muscle tone","Slight increase in tone with catch followed by minimal resistance through less than half of ROM","Considerable increase in tone making passive movement difficult","Affected part rigid in flexion or extension"],t.s)
B.Rw=new A.t('On the Modified Ashworth Scale, a grade of "1+" indicates:',B.JU,1,"The Modified Ashworth Scale: 0 = no increase in tone, 1 = slight increase with catch and release at end of range, 1+ = slight increase with catch followed by minimal resistance through <1/2 of ROM, 2 = more marked increase through most ROM, 3 = considerable increase making passive movement difficult, 4 = rigid.")
B.GZ=s(["Begin early intervention services based on the Denver II result alone","Perform a diagnostic evaluation using the Bayley-4","Repeat the Denver II in 6 months","Order brain MRI before any further assessment"],t.s)
B.QL=new A.t("A 2-year-old screens positive on the Denver II for possible developmental delay. What is the most appropriate next step?",B.GZ,1,"The Denver II is a screening tool with high sensitivity but limited specificity (significant false-positive rate). A positive screen should always be followed by a diagnostic evaluation such as the Bayley-4, which is the gold standard for infant developmental assessment (ages 1-42 months) and provides norm-referenced scores identifying presence and severity of delay.")
B.JP=s(["AAC should be delayed until speech therapy has been attempted for at least 2 years","AAC does NOT inhibit speech development and can facilitate verbal language acquisition","AAC is only appropriate after age 5 when speech potential can be fully assessed","AAC replaces the need for speech therapy and should be used exclusively"],t.s)
B.Ov=new A.t("A family expresses concern that introducing augmentative and alternative communication (AAC) for their nonverbal 3-year-old will prevent the child from developing speech. What does the evidence show?",B.JP,1,"Research consistently demonstrates that AAC does not inhibit speech development. Rather, it can facilitate verbal language acquisition by reducing communication frustration and providing a scaffold for language learning. Current best practice calls for early introduction of AAC alongside speech therapy as part of a multimodal communication approach.")
B.J4=s(["Head","Trunk","Pelvis","Lower extremities"],t.s)
B.R7=new A.t("When performing a wheelchair seating assessment, which body segment must be stabilized FIRST according to the seating hierarchy?",B.J4,2,'The seating hierarchy follows a strict bottom-up sequence: pelvis first, then trunk, then head. Proximal stability enables distal function. "Fix the pelvis, free the hands" \u2014 a child with an unstable pelvis will use upper extremities for postural support rather than functional activities.')
B.EH=s(["0-3 years","3-5 years","5-21 years","0-21 years"],t.s)
B.Q1=new A.t("IDEA Part C provides early intervention services for children ages:",B.EH,0,"IDEA Part C covers early intervention for ages 0-3 using an IFSP (Individualized Family Service Plan). Part B covers special education for ages 3-21 using an IEP (Individualized Education Program).")
B.Gp=s(["WeeFIM","PEDI","Bayley Scales","Denver II"],t.s)
B.Q7=new A.t("Which pediatric outcome measure is considered the gold standard for infant developmental assessment?",B.Gp,2,"The Bayley Scales of Infant and Toddler Development (Bayley-4) is the gold standard for developmental assessment in infants ages 1-42 months. Denver II is a SCREENING tool, not diagnostic.")
B.Jy=s(["GMFCS measures change over time while GMFM does not","GMFCS is a classification system while GMFM is an evaluative measure","GMFCS is for adults while GMFM is for children","They measure the same thing using different scales"],t.s)
B.Oc=new A.t("The key difference between GMFCS and GMFM is:",B.Jy,1,"GMFCS is a CLASSIFICATION system (stable, does not change over time). GMFM is an EVALUATIVE measure (detects change over time). GMFCS classifies severity; GMFM measures functional capacity.")
B.J5=s(["IEP in the least restrictive school environment","IFSP in natural environments (home, daycare, community)","504 plan in the general education classroom","IEP in a center-based early intervention facility"],t.s)
B.Qj=new A.t("IDEA Part C provides early intervention services using which service plan, delivered in which setting?",B.J5,1,"IDEA Part C (birth to 3 years) uses an Individualized Family Service Plan (IFSP) delivered in natural environments \u2014 the settings where the child and family naturally spend their time. Part B (ages 3-21) uses an IEP in the least restrictive environment.")
B.JO=s(["IFSP; transition planning begins at age 12","IEP; transition planning begins by age 16 (some states age 14)","504 plan; transition planning begins at age 18","IEP; transition planning begins at age 21"],t.s)
B.Q8=new A.t("IDEA Part B provides special education services for children ages 3-21 using which plan, and transition planning must begin by what age?",B.JO,1,"Part B uses an IEP (Individualized Education Program), is child/student-centered, and delivered in the least restrictive environment. IDEA mandates transition planning beginning no later than age 16 (some states require age 14). Annual IEP review and re-evaluation every 3 years are required.")
B.G4=s(["IFSP addresses only motor goals while IEP addresses cognitive goals","IFSP is family-centered with the family as the unit of service; IEP is child/student-centered","IFSP is funded by schools while IEP is funded by health departments","IFSP requires physician orders while IEP does not"],t.s)
B.Ra=new A.t("The fundamental philosophical difference between the IFSP (Part C) and the IEP (Part B) is:",B.G4,1,"The IFSP is family-centered, addressing family outcomes and priorities with the family as the unit of service. The IEP is child/student-centered and education-focused. This philosophical shift at the Part C to Part B transition at age 3 is a core board concept.")
B.JV=s(["IEP under IDEA Part B","Section 504 plan","IFSP under IDEA Part C","No plan needed; this is standard school nursing"],t.s)
B.PR=new A.t("A student with well-controlled diabetes needs blood glucose monitoring and snack accommodations at school but does not require specially designed instruction. Which plan is most appropriate?",B.JV,1,"Section 504 of the Rehabilitation Act provides accommodations for students whose disability substantially limits a major life activity but who do not need specially designed instruction (and thus do not qualify for an IEP). Common 504 scenarios include diabetes, epilepsy, ADHD without special education needs, food allergies, and asthma.")
B.Hs=s(["Age 18 when transfer to adult care occurs","Age 12-14 with establishment of a transition policy","Age 21 at the time of IDEA graduation","Age 8-10 during early school years"],t.s)
B.P9=new A.t("According to the Got Transition framework, at what age should healthcare transition planning begin?",B.Hs,1,"The Got Transition 6 Core Elements framework recommends: (1) Transition Policy at age 12-14, (2) Tracking at 14-18, (3) Readiness assessment at 14-18, (4) Planning at 14-18, (5) Transfer of Care at 18-21, and (6) Transfer Completion at 18-26. Early start allows time to build self-management and self-advocacy skills.")
B.K7=s(["A residential facility providing 24-hour medical care for children with disabilities","A model of primary care delivery that is accessible, continuous, comprehensive, family-centered, and coordinated","A hospital-based rehabilitation unit for complex medical management","An insurance plan that covers all pediatric rehabilitation services"],t.s)
B.PZ=new A.t("The AAP Medical Home model is best described as:",B.K7,1,"The medical home is NOT a physical location \u2014 it is a model of delivering primary care. It emphasizes physician-directed, team-based care with a whole-child approach, care coordination across settings, and enhanced access. It serves as the hub for coordinating medical, rehabilitation, education, and community services.")
B.K3=s(["SSI is means-tested based on income/resources; SSDI-DAC is based on a parent's Social Security earnings record and is NOT means-tested","SSI is available only to adults; SSDI-DAC is for children under 18","Both programs are means-tested and require limited income","SSDI-DAC requires the individual to have their own work history"],t.s)
B.Rv=new A.t("Which statement correctly distinguishes SSI from SSDI Disabled Adult Child (DAC) benefits?",B.K3,0,"SSI is means-tested \u2014 family income and resources must be below thresholds. SSDI-DAC benefits are drawn from a parent's Social Security earnings record (parent must be retired, disabled, or deceased) and are NOT means-tested. DAC benefits require disability onset before age 22.")
B.G2=s(["Benefits automatically terminate at age 18","Eligibility is redetermined using adult disability criteria, counting only the individual's own income and resources","The family's income continues to be the primary factor","SSI converts automatically to SSDI"],t.s)
B.PX=new A.t("When a child receiving SSI turns 18, what critical change occurs in eligibility determination?",B.G2,1,"At age 18, SSI eligibility is redetermined using adult disability criteria. Critically, only the individual's own income and resources are counted, not the family's. Some children who qualified based on family income may lose eligibility, while others previously ineligible due to high family income may now qualify.")
B.If=s(["SDM removes all legal rights; guardianship preserves them","Under SDM the individual retains ALL legal decision-making authority with trusted supporters; under full guardianship the individual loses legal decision-making rights","SDM and full guardianship provide identical legal protections","SDM is only available for financial decisions, not medical ones"],t.s)
B.Pp=new A.t("How does supported decision-making (SDM) differ from full guardianship for a young adult with intellectual disability?",B.If,1,"Under supported decision-making, the individual retains ALL legal rights but designates trusted supporters who help understand information and weigh options. Supporters cannot override choices. Full guardianship removes legal decision-making authority. The trend in disability rights favors the least restrictive alternative.")
B.Hj=s(["GMFCS level","Cognitive ability / IQ","Type of CP (spastic vs dyskinetic)","Age at first therapy intervention"],t.s)
B.P5=new A.t("What is the single strongest predictor of employment outcomes in adults with cerebral palsy?",B.Hj,1,"Research identifies cognitive ability/IQ as the single strongest predictor of employment in adults with CP. Other significant predictors include ambulation status, speech/communication ability, and hand function/manual ability (MACS level). This has practical implications for maximizing educational programming and managing conditions that impair cognition.")
B.FQ=s(["Low back pain","Hip pain from subluxation","Neck pain","Knee pain from crouch gait"],t.s)
B.Qk=new A.t("What is the most common musculoskeletal complaint in adults with cerebral palsy?",B.FQ,2,"Neck pain is the most common musculoskeletal complaint in adults with CP (60-80% prevalence), caused by chronic abnormal head/neck posturing, accelerated cervical degenerative changes, and prolonged wheelchair use. In dyskinetic CP with cervical dystonia, cervical myelopathy may develop and requires monitoring.")
B.FR=s(["5%","15%","40%","70%"],t.s)
B.Of=new A.t("In individuals with spina bifida between ages 5 and 30, approximately what percentage of deaths are attributable to urologic/renal complications?",B.FR,2,"Approximately 40% of deaths in individuals with spina bifida between ages 5-30 are urologic/renal in origin (chronic renal failure from reflux, hydronephrosis, recurrent pyelonephritis). This makes lifelong urologic surveillance among the most important elements of spina bifida care. Shunt complications are the second major cause of mortality.")
B.Hp=s(["The best possible education available",'Sufficient to provide "some educational benefit" regardless of severity',"Reasonably calculated to enable progress appropriate in light of the child's circumstances","Identical to the education provided to non-disabled peers"],t.s)
B.QP=new A.t("The 2017 Supreme Court case Endrew F. v. Douglas County School District raised the FAPE standard to require that an IEP must be:",B.Hp,2,'Endrew F. (2017) replaced the prior minimal standard from Rowley (1982) that required only "some educational benefit." The new standard requires that IEPs be "reasonably calculated to enable a child to make progress appropriate in light of the child\'s circumstances," demanding meaningful, individualized progress even for children with severe disabilities.')
B.EN=s(["Self-contained special education classroom","General education classroom with supports","Separate school for students with disabilities","Homebound instruction"],t.s)
B.PV=new A.t("The Least Restrictive Environment (LRE) continuum under IDEA ranges from least to most restrictive. Which is the LEAST restrictive placement?",B.EN,1,"The LRE continuum from least to most restrictive: (1) general education with supports, (2) general education with resource room, (3) self-contained special education classroom, (4) separate school, (5) homebound instruction, (6) hospital/institutional setting. IDEA mandates education alongside non-disabled peers to the maximum extent appropriate.")
B.F3=s(["Malignant hyperthermia with dantrolene-resistant rigidity","Fatal hyperkalemia and rhabdomyolysis","Prolonged neuromuscular blockade lasting days","Anaphylactic reaction to the vehicle solution"],t.s)
B.PH=new A.t("Succinylcholine is absolutely contraindicated in patients with Duchenne muscular dystrophy because it can trigger:",B.F3,1,"Succinylcholine is absolutely contraindicated in DMD because it can trigger fatal hyperkalemia and rhabdomyolysis due to the underlying dystrophinopathy. Cardiac arrest may be the initial presentation, even in patients not yet diagnosed with DMD. Total intravenous anesthesia (TIVA) is recommended. This risk extends to female carriers of DMD mutations as well.")
